
      Identification Of Problem



Identification of Problem

     For my computing project, I have decided to write a computer game.
This will be of the puzzle genre, and I will also design and implement a
level designer utility, which will allow either me or another user to
easily design levels for the game. A fuller description of the game style
will be detailed later.


Justification for Project

     I chose this project for a number of reasons. Firstly, it is a
project I actually want to program. The game is loosely based on an old
Commodore 64 public domain game, which I really enjoyed when I had that
computer. The game successfully combined both tactical thinking and the
need for arcade dexterity. Now I have upgraded to a more powerful machine,
I often wish I could still play the game. So instead of waiting for
someone else to release a similar game, I decided to program it myself:
this way I could also add more features to the game, which will hopefully
improve the depth of the game, and of course improve the aesthetics of it.

     Secondly, the project should be an interesting challenge. I spend a
good deal of my time actually playing games, and it will be entertaining
to follow the process of planning, designing, documenting and programming
a game in the same way that commercial games are (but on a smaller scale,
obviously).


Identification of User

     Although I was initially producing the game for my own use, I am
designing it with a view to it being distributed in the public domain. 
This will force me to be more professional in my system design, make me
produce a more user-friendly interface and also ensure that the programs
are reliable and basically foolproof. This wouldn't have been necessary if
I was programming the game for my own use, as I would know what could and
couldn't be done, and how to do it.

     Other aspects of the system will also have to be modified slightly.
As most PD games are distributed on disk only, without any manuals or
packaging, there will have to be on-disk documentation as to how to use
the system. This could allow possibilities such as hypertext, which would
have to be looked into.

     As it is basically a tile based puzzle game, there isn't really a
target age for the proposed user.  Puzzle games, in general, have a wide
appeal across all age ranges, from about 10-12 years upwards.  A good
example of this is Lemmings, an extremely popular puzzle game with old and
young alike.


