        Present Game Design



Outline

     In this section, the present game as it stands will be described. The
improvements to the game that I am considering making will be documented
in the following section.  The design of the actual system and programs
needed to create the game will be looked at in the Design section.


Brief description of game

     As mentioned previously, the game is one of the puzzle genre.  The
player controls a craft that he moves around the game screen.  The screen
consists of a variety of tiles, each of which has a purpose, such as
having to be destroyed, restricting the movement of the player, certain
death, and so on.  The tiles in the present game are described in detail
below.

     The screen will consist of an arrangement of tiles in a rectangle,
around 20 tiles across and 10 tiles down.  The player's craft is about the
size of 1 tile, and can move either up, down, left or right in increments
of one tile.  Spaces are also allowed in this grid: if the player moves
his craft into either a space (where there is no tile) or out of the range
of the grid, then the craft is destroyed.

     There is one special type of tile that is "destructible".  It is
destroyed by the player moving onto the tile, and then moving off it.  The
aim of the game is for the player to destroy all the destructible tiles,
and then to move to an "Exit" tile.  This will complete a level, and the
player will proceed to play the next level.

     This is a brief description of the game style, and should become
clearer as the project progresses.


Types of tile

Normal: Has no adverse effect on the player. He can move around on these
freely.

Destructible: These have to all be destroyed before the player can exit
the level.

Double-Destructible: These too have to be destroyed, but the player can
either travel over these once or twice to destroy them.

Teleports: When landing on one of these tiles, the user can teleport to
another predetermined tile on the level.

Vertical/Horizontal only: These are similar to normal tiles, but can only
be entered and left by certain sides of the tile.

Exit: This is the tile the player must reach after destroying all the
appropriate blocks to complete the level.

No Tile: If the player encounters either the edge of the grid of tiles, or
a space in the map, the player's craft will be destroyed.


Basic Game Structure

     The player will start with a certain number of lives, this amount
decreasing every time the player dies. When this happens, the current
level is reset to it's initial state, and the player can then attempt it
again. A scoring scheme is also used, although there is no way to compare
different players other than to note down the scores manually.  If a level
is successfully completed, the next level is then attempted.  If all a
player's lives are lost, he must then restart the game at the very first
level.


