         Game Improvements



Deficiencies of Current Game

     As it stands, the game is very good: the game structure is original,
the levels are well designed, and the control method is easy to use. 
However, this is not to say that it can't be improved, which is what I
will be attempting to achieve in my project.


Suggestions for improvement

     Here I will outline some ways in which I think the game system could
be improved: I will later examine these suggestions in more depth.

- More tile types.  These will have different effects on the player, and
allow for a more complex, sophisticated, level design.
- The inclusion of time limits for the levels
- Allowing passwords to be used to skip levels
- A high score table
- A way to edit and design new levels


More tile types

     Having sat down and thought about this quite a lot, I came to the
conclusion that the original set of tiles was somewhat comprehensive. 
Indeed, the variety of the levels in the original game paid testament to
this.  I did manage, however, to come up with a few more tile types that
the game could benefit from.

     The first two types affect the movement of the player in the level:
the second two will control access to different parts of the level.

Ice: The player slides over these tiles in the direction they were
travelling, with no control until they reach another type of tile.

Arrows: These send the player in the direction of the arrow: the player
has no control until another type of tile is reached.

Switches and Switchable blocks: When a switch tile is activated, a
switchable block is deactivated. Initially, the switchable blocks can
either be lethal (i.e. the player is destroyed on contact with such a
tile) or normal. One switch can control up to two of these blocks,
toggling them between lethal and normal blocks.


Time Limits

     Initially, I had apprehensions about adding a time limit to levels,
whereby the player's craft is destroyed if the level isn't completed in a
certain time.  After all, it is a puzzle game, and the levels should be
thought about, mused over, a route decided, and then executed.  If a time
limit was implemented, all the player would do if he were stuck on a level
would be to sketch the level onto paper, and think about it then.  This
would be a waste of time and paper and could easily be avoided.

     I then hit upon the idea of making time limits optional. If the
player completes the level within a certain time, he gets bonus points: if
he doesn't, he doesn't.  Either way, the level is complete and the player
will move to the next one.  This will provide the experienced player who
is replaying the level an extra goal to achieve.  In fact, different
strategies may have to be employed to complete it in the least time
possible.


High Scores and Passwords

     A high score table will be implemented, whereby the scores and names
of the best players will be stored and displayed.  I also hope to be able
to let the user save these scores to disk, so they are not lost when the
computer is turned off.

     Passwords will also be used, to allow the experienced player who has
played the game previously to bypass the earlier, tedious levels (most
levels will become slightly boring once they have been completed once). 
This was one of the greatest deficiencies of the original game, as when
the player was stuck on the 23rd level, he would be allowed 5 tries (or
however many lives he had) and would then have to complete the previous 22
levels again to get back to the point they were previously at.


Level Editor

     One of the biggest improvements to the game would be a way to edit
and create new levels.  This would allow players to set their own
challenging levels, and possibly distribute these to others who own the
game.  The level editor will be described in much more detail in the
Design section.


